Task 1: Scrape raw data

library(rvest)
## Loading required package: xml2
## 
## Attaching package: 'rvest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     pluck
## The following object is masked from 'package:readr':
## 
##     guess_encoding
page <- "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_nuclear_reactors"
tableList <- page %>%
  read_html() %>%
  html_nodes(css = "table") %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)
Japan <-
  tableList[[22]]
Japan

If we ignore the first row, the data is tidy. The data is not tidy because the first row is redundant with the variable names, that makes it has different format with other rows, and the first row cant represent a case.

Task 2: Tidy Data & Data Cleaning

# you may want to do your own investigation to understand why this line is needed
names(Japan)[c(3,7)] <- c("type", "grossMW")

Japan <-
  Japan %>%
  filter(row_number() > 1) %>%
  rename(name = Name, 
         reactor = `UnitNo.`,
         model = Reactor,
         status = Status, 
         netMW = `Capacity in MW`,
         construction = `Construction start`,
         operation = `Commercial operation`, 
         closure = Closure)
str(Japan)
## 'data.frame':    64 obs. of  10 variables:
##  $ name        : chr  "Fugen" "Fukushima Daiichi" "Fukushima Daiichi" "Fukushima Daiichi" ...
##  $ reactor     : chr  "1" "1" "2" "3" ...
##  $ type        : chr  "HWLWR" "BWR" "BWR" "BWR" ...
##  $ model       : chr  "ATR" "BWR-3" "BWR-4" "BWR-4" ...
##  $ status      : chr  "Shut down" "Inoperable" "Inoperable" "Inoperable" ...

##  $ grossMW     : chr  "165" "460" "784" "784" ...

##  $ operation   : chr  "20 March 1979" "26 March 1971" "18 July 1974" "27 March 1976" ...
##  $ closure     : chr  "29 March 2003" "19 May 2011" "19 May 2011" "19 May 2011" ...
Japan <-
  Japan %>%
  mutate(netMW = as.numeric(netMW), 
         grossMW = as.numeric(grossMW),
         construction = dmy(construction),
         operation = dmy(operation),
         closure = dmy(closure))

Japan

Task 3: Plot Net Generation Capacity vs Construction Date

Japan %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = netMW, y = construction)) + geom_point() + aes(colour=type)
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The FBR, GCR, HWLWR were used rarely, and after 1990, they were not used. The BWR and PWR are used most often until today.

Task 4: Scrape & Clean China Data

China <-
tableList[[10]]
names(China)[c(3,7)] <- c("type", "grossMW")

China <-
  China %>%
  filter(row_number() > 1) %>%
  rename(name = Name, 
         reactor = `UnitNo.`,
         model = Reactor,
         status = Status, 
         netMW = `Capacity in MW`,
         construction = `Construction start`,
         operation = `Commercial operation`, 
         closure = Closure)
China <-
  China %>%
  mutate(netMW = as.numeric(netMW), 
         grossMW = as.numeric(grossMW),
         construction = dmy(construction),
         operation = dmy(operation),
         closure = dmy(closure))
## Warning: 7 failed to parse.
## Warning: 16 failed to parse.
China
Japan <- 
  Japan %>% mutate(country = "Japan") 
China <- 
  China %>% mutate(country = "China") 
Japan_China <- rbind(Japan, China)
Japan_China

Task 5: Reconstruct Info Graphic of Japan Reactors

Japan %>% 
  mutate(reactorID = paste(name, reactor)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = operation, y = reactorID, colour=type, shape = status)) + geom_segment(aes(x = construction, xend=operation, yend = reactorID))
